properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant rainfall, mild temperatures, and snow melt are expected Sunday through Sunday night. Showers or periods of rain are expected over the next few days. While no significant amounts are forecast for tonight, rainfall is expected to intensify on Sunday into Sunday night and may require a rainfall warning. Rainfall warnings have been issued for areas of the west coast of Newfoundland, north of the Codroy Valley. Rainfall amounts of 5 to 10 mm are currently expected to fall Sunday night, however the potential for amounts reaching 25 mm remains a possibility. Rain will combine with mild temperatures to cause significant snowmelt and an increased potential for localized flooding. The public is advised to follow subsequent forecasts and updates as rainfall warnings may need to be issued. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
Expires: 2019-04-21T08:49:10-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-04-21T00:50:10-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.1941942172.2019

properties.Title: Update: Flood Warning Continues For The Red River From Emerson To The Red River Floodway Channel Inlet
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre continues to issue a Flood Warning on the Red River from Emerson to the Red River Floodway channel inlet due to high water flows. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions given by local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.
Expires: 2019-04-21T10:30:00-05:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Manitoba Emergency Measures Organization, 2019-04-20T10:18:03-05:00, 28639CBB-7892-EA7A-3538-2735006C9200
Area: Red River from Emerson to the Red River Floodway channel inlet

properties.Title: Update: A High Water Advisory Continues For The Saskatchewan And Carrot Rivers Near The Town Of The Pas
properties.Summary:
Description: Update: This is a Manitoba Emergency Alert. Manitoba Infrastructure's Hydrologic Forecast Centre continues to issue a High Water Advisory for the Saskatchewan and Carrot Rivers near the Town of The Pas. River levels are currently rising which may cause ice jamming during the melt and ice break-up period. If you are in the affected area, be watchful of local waterways as flooding is likely to occur. Do not attempt to cross fast flowing waters or waters of unknown depth. Avoid flooded areas. Follow all directions by the local authorities. Listen for updates and take all necessary precautions to stay safe. Up-to-date information is available at www.gov.mb.ca/flooding and www.manitoba511.ca or stay tuned to local media.

properties.Title: Fog Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Near zero visibility in fog is expected or occurring. Winds will become light this evening. With all the moisture on the ground from the recent rain, conditions are favourable for the formation of fog. Widespread fog is expected to develop later this evening and persist well into Sunday morning. Fog should dissipate by noon Sunday. ### Visibility may be significantly and suddenly reduced to near zero. Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
Expires: 2019-04-21T17:50:59-00:00

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Rainfall, combined with melting snow, is expected. The frozen ground has a reduced ability to absorb this rainfall. Showers will intensify today into tonight with rainfall amounts of 15 to 25 mm expected by early Monday morning. The potential for higher amounts exists, especially over higher elevations where accumulations could reach and potentially exceed 50 mm. Furthermore, the rain will combine with mild temperatures to cause significant snowmelt and an increased potential for localized flooding. Showers are expected to taper off by noon on Monday. ### Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
